3 Creating a map

First I will read the hexbin in geojson format and ‘fortify’ it so I can use it with ggplot2 later The hexbin in geojson is available here

US <- geojson_read(here('data', 'us_states_hexgrid.geojson'),  what = "sp")
US@data = US@data %>% 
  mutate(google_name = gsub(" \\(United States\\)", "", google_name))

US_map <- tidy(US, region = "google_name")

We now have ageospatial object!!!! Next will be calculating the centroid of hexagon.

centroids <- cbind.data.frame(data.frame(data.frame(gCentroid(US, byid=TRUE),
                                                    id = US@data$iso3166_2)))

Now we can do a bit of plotting

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = US_map, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = "slateblue", color = "white") +
  geom_text(data = centroids, aes(x = x, y = y, label = id)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_map()

My idea is to colour the hexagons according to the income data. So it is basically a cloropeth map.

So now we need to load the data and do a basic exploration before getting to integrate it with the map.

The data can be found here

housing %>%

  ggplot(aes(x = `Income Level`, y = `Number of Households`, fill = State, size = `Percent of Total` * 100)) + geom_point(shape = 21) + theme_classic()
